Now using these counts we need to create a contingency table. In order to do this we will use pivot_wider(). Inside pivot_wider(), "names_from = third_pitch" forces each unique third_pitch to now become a column. Then, "values_from = n" designates what goes inside each column, row combination. Lastly, "values_fill = 0" ensures that any missing combinations (e.g. a particular (state, third_pitch) that didnt occur) get a zero instead of NA. Then, "column_to_rownames("state")", moves the state column out of the body and into the row names of the data frame. Then, "as.matrix" changes this from a data_frame to a matrix. Lastly, "prop.table(margin = 1)", creates proportions such that every row sums to 1.




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
transition_matrix <- state_counts %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from   = third_pitch, values_from  = n, values_fill  = 0) %>%
  column_to_rownames("state") %>%
  as.matrix() %>%
  prop.table(margin = 1)

transition_matrix
```

